g.text: It could be that the process to create a new object is to expensive and a copy is sufficient. E.g. a database call is made when an object is instantiated. Instead, we can make a copy and ‘shape’ it to fit our use-case.

g.title: Rectangle.9
g.desc: The amount of sub-classes pollute the code
g.text: The amount of sub-classes pollute the code

g.title: Folded Corner.11
g.desc: Using the Factory method pattern can cause a parallel hierarc...

g.text: Using the Factory method pattern can cause a parallel hierarchy to our product hierarchy. These factory sub- classes only differ in the product they instantiate. To reduce the amount of parallel hierarchies we can use the Prototype pattern. By applying Prototype pattern, we make product creation (=cloning) part of the product itself. The prototype pattern in combination with dependency injection can ensure a reduction in sub-classing. On top of that, we can sometimes apply the same reduction in the product class hierarchy. During runtime we can clone a product, slightly modify its internal state and have both variants without the need of sub-classing.

g.title: Rectangle.14
g.desc: The process to create a new object is too difficult
g.text: The process to create a new object is too difficult

g.title: Folded Corner.18
g.desc: It could be that creating an object is difficult in terms of ...

g.text: It could be that creating an object is difficult in terms of parameters and/or dependencies. Making the clone operation part of the product itself, releases this responsibility from the client. This ensures that the client does not need familiarity with the concrete type and its necessary dependencies.

g.title: Rectangle.21
g.desc: Clients need to copy without familiarity with the concrete type
g.text: Clients need to copy without familiarity with the concrete type

g.title: Folded Corner.23
g.desc: Prototype pattern is called ‘Virtual Copy Constructor’, becau...

g.text: Prototype pattern is called ‘Virtual Copy Constructor’, because clients can copy the underlying concrete type while interfering with an abstraction. This could be convenient because our clients don’t need and cannot interfere with the underlying concrete type. We introduce a restriction, but still provide a way to instantiate/copy a new instance of that class. This reduces coupling and prevents the clients from bringing the underlying concrete type in an undefined state. Introducing a ‘prototype manager’ can even reduce the coupling of first instantiation. The prototype manager/registry will contain a set of predefined objects whom we can clone and only use via its base class. This provides a centralized point where we can get new prototype instances, but also have a default prototype saved that we can ‘shape’ when copying.

g.title: Folded Corner.20
g.desc: The unfamiliarity with the underlying type while making a cop...

g.text: The unfamiliarity with the underlying type while making a copy reduces the coupling between the client and the concrete type. Reduction in coupling means preventing changes in the client when the underlying concrete type changes. On top of that, we restrict the client to just use the base class/interface. This restriction provides more encapsulation. Encapsulation ensures that our clients cannot force our system in an undefined state, resulting in fewer bugs.

g.title: Rectangle.31
g.desc: The process to get the object in a defined state is time cons...
g.text: The process to get the object in a defined state is time consuming/difficult

g.title: Folded Corner.36
g.desc: Our system or library should provide a possibility to make co...

g.text: Our system or library should provide a possibility to make copies without exposure of the concrete underlying type. E.g. copies we could need, because creating a new object via a factory is ‘expensive’. Being able to copy via a base class prevents our clients from being coupled to a concrete type. This provides a way to introduce different concrete types without having to modify our client.

g.text: Object re-creation is not ‘expensive’ and a factory method is sufficient

g.title: Folded Corner.48
g.desc: It could be labor intensive and difficult to provide copy beh...

g.text: It could be labor intensive and difficult to provide copy behavior for certain objects. Providing copy behavior for a object means its dependencies and the dependencies of its dependencies also require copy ‘behavior’. It should be considered carefully if object re-creation is expensive and sub-classing starts to pollute our code base.
